"Ehlers A., Worm B., Reusch T.B.H.","Importance of genetic diversity in eelgrass Zostera marina for its resilience to global warming",2008,"Marine Ecology Progress Series","355",,,"1","7",,,10.3354/meps07369,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-41349117432&partnerID=40&md5=5dde847cb2800afb5a7e60706de0a942","Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, IfM-Geomar, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, 24105 Kiel, Germany; Max-Planck-Institute for Limnology, August-Thienemann-Str. 2, 24306 Plön, Germany; Biology Department, Dalhousie University, Halifax, NS B3H 4J1, Canada; Institute for Evolution and Biodiversity, University of Münster, Hüfferstr. 1, 48149 Münster, Germany","Ehlers, A., Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, IfM-Geomar, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, 24105 Kiel, Germany, Max-Planck-Institute for Limnology, August-Thienemann-Str. 2, 24306 Plön, Germany; Worm, B., Leibniz Institute for Marine Sciences, IfM-Geomar, Düsternbrooker Weg 20, 24105 Kiel, Germany, Biology Department, Dalhousie University, Halifax, NS B3H 4J1, Canada; Reusch, T.B.H., Max-Planck-Institute for Limnology, August-Thienemann-Str. 2, 24306 Plön, Germany, Institute for Evolution and Biodiversity, University of Münster, Hüfferstr. 1, 48149 Münster, Germany","Effects of global warming on marine ecosystems are far less understood than they are in terrestrial environments. Macrophyte-based coastal ecosystems are particularly vulnerable to global warming, because they often lack species redundancy. We tested whether summer heat waves have negative effects on an ecologically important ecosystem engineer, the eelgrass Zostera marina L., and whether high genotypic diversity may provide resilience in the face of climatic extremes. In a mesocosm experiment, we manipulated genotypic diversity of eelgrass patches fully crossed with water temperature (control vs. temperature stress) over 5 mo. We found a strong negative effect of warming and a positive effect of genotypic diversity on shoot densities of eelgrass. These results suggest that eelgrass meadows and associated ecosystem services will be negatively affected by predicted increases in summer temperature extremes. Genotypic diversity may provide critical response diversity for maintaining seagrass ecosystem functioning, and for adaptation to environmental change. © Inter-Research 2008.","Climate change; Coastal ecosystem; Genotypic diversity; Intraspecific variation; Ocean warming; Resilience; Zostera marina","adaptation; climate effect; ecosystem function; ecosystem service; environmental change; genetic variation; genotype; global warming; interspecific variation; mesocosm; seagrass; Zostera marina",,,,,,"Allison, G., The influence of species diversity and stress intensity on community resistance and resilience (2004) Ecol Monogr, 74, pp. 117-134; Applied Biosystems (2001) GenScan Analysis Software (3.1) and Genotyper Software (2.0). Applied Biosystems, Foster City, CABACC Lead Author Group (2006) Assessment of Climate Change for the Baltic Sea Basin - The BACC Project, International BALTEX Secretariat Publication No. 35. GKSS, GeesthachtBeniston, M., Stephenson, D.B., Christensen, O.B., Ferro, C.A.T., and others, Future extreme events in European climate: An exploration of regional climate model projections (2007) Clim Change, 81, pp. 71-95; Bintz, J.C., Nixon, S.W., Buckley, B.A., Granger, S.L., Impacts of temperature and nutrients on coastal lagoon plant communities (2003) Estuaries, 26, pp. 765-776; Borum, J., Sand-Jensen, K., Binzer, T., Pedersen, O., Greve, T.M., Oxygen movement in seagrasses (2006) Seagrasses: Biology, ecology and conservation, pp. 255-270. , Larkum AWD, Orth RJ, Duarte CM eds, Springer, Dordrecht, p; Bruno, J.F., Stachowicz, J.J., Bertness, M.D., Inclusion of facilitation into ecological theory (2003) Trends Ecol Evol, 18, pp. 119-125; Duarte, C.M., The future of seagrass meadows (2002) Environ Conserv, 29, pp. 192-206; Duffy, J.E., Biodiversity and the functioning of seagrass ecosystems